FMD Outbreak Reported in Primorye, Russia
-------------------------------------------
Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD) has been found on a private farm in the village of Usachevka, in the Primorye region – also known as Primorsky Krai – in the far south-eastern corner of the country.

The outbreak affected 6 cows and one sheep, of the 240 cattle, 35 sheep, 12 goats and 10 pigs susceptible reports Rosselkhoznadzor veterinary services.

The source of the outbreak is currently unknown.

Usachevka is located 45 km from the border between Russia and China.

Primorsky Krai is part of the buffer zone where cattle and small livestock are annually vaccinated against FMD.

All the necessary measures to suppress the outbreak and prevent the spread of the disease are being taken.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>



[The above information was probably derived from press release No 44, dated 2 Mar 2012, in the Russian web-site of Rosselkhoznadzor.

Details on the FMD serotype involved and the vaccination history of the affected livestock are anticipated.

The Primorye region was last infected by FMD during 2005.

For the location of Usachevka, see map at http://healthmap.org/r/1WcG.- Mod.AS

